# Issue a credential with a custom namespace

Use this guidance if your credential type does not use ISO/IEC 18013-5.1 standard
attributes. You will need to define a custom namespace containing data elements
specific to your service. This page uses a fictional sheep licence as a worked
example throughout.

## When to use a custom namespace

The ISO/IEC 18013-5.1 standard defines data elements for driving licences —
attributes such as `family_name`, `birth_date`, and `driving_privileges`. If your
credential maps onto those attributes, use the standard namespace `org.iso.18013.5.1`
and follow the [Create an mdoc credential](/issue-a-credential/mdoc/) guidance.

Most new government credential types will need a custom namespace. If your credential
has no overlap with driving licence attributes — for example a sheep licence, a
professional registration, or a benefit entitlement — you must define your own
namespace to contain your data elements.

## Agree your docType and namespace with the GOV.UK Wallet team

Before you write any code, contact the GOV.UK Wallet onboarding team to agree:

- your `docType` string
- your namespace string
- the data elements you want to include and their data types

The GOV.UK Wallet team maintains a registry of docTypes to prevent two issuers
from using the same value. Your credential will not be accepted by GOV.UK Wallet
until your docType is registered.

<%= warning_text('Do not use a docType or namespace in production until you have confirmed it with the GOV.UK Wallet onboarding team. Using an unregistered docType will cause GOV.UK Wallet to reject your credential.') %>

## Name your docType and namespace

### Naming convention

Use a reverse-domain-name format to make your docType and namespace globally
unique. For UK government departments, this starts with `uk.gov.`, followed by
your department's identifier, then the credential name in lowercase with hyphens.

### docType

The `docType` identifies the document type. It does not include a version suffix,
because versioning is handled through the GOV.UK Wallet onboarding process:

```
uk.gov.defra.sheep-licence
```

### Namespace

The namespace scopes data elements within the credential. It includes a version
suffix so that future changes to your element set can be versioned independently:

```
uk.gov.defra.sheep-licence.1
```

### Worked example — the sheep licence

The Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs (DEFRA) is issuing a digital
sheep licence. The values agreed with the GOV.UK Wallet team are:

| Field | Value |
|---|---|
| `docType` | `uk.gov.defra.sheep-licence` |
| Namespace | `uk.gov.defra.sheep-licence.1` |

## Design your data elements

Work with the GOV.UK Wallet onboarding team to agree the data elements for your
namespace. Each element needs an identifier, a data type, a mandatory flag, a
description, and an example value.

Choose identifiers that are unambiguous and consistent with how your back-end
systems refer to the data. Use `snake_case`. Avoid abbreviations. Once agreed
and deployed, element identifiers cannot be changed without creating a new
namespace version.

For the CBOR data type encodings to use, see the
[data element encoding reference](/issue-a-credential/mdoc/#data-element-encoding-reference)
on the main mdoc page.

### Sheep licence data elements

| Element identifier | Data type | Mandatory | Description | Example |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| `licence_number` | String | Yes | Unique DEFRA-assigned identifier for this licence. | `SL-2024-00847` |
| `holder_family_name` | String | Yes | Family name of the licence holder as registered with DEFRA. | `Shepherd` |
| `holder_given_name` | String | Yes | Given name(s) of the licence holder as registered with DEFRA. | `James Robert` |
| `holder_date_of_birth` | Full date (CBOR tag 1004) | Yes | Date of birth of the licence holder, formatted `YYYY-MM-DD`. | `1972-04-15` |
| `issue_date` | Full date (CBOR tag 1004) | Yes | Date this licence was issued, formatted `YYYY-MM-DD`. | `2024-01-10` |
| `expiry_date` | Full date (CBOR tag 1004) | Yes | Date this licence expires, formatted `YYYY-MM-DD`. | `2025-01-09` |
| `sheep_count` | Integer | Yes | Total number of sheep covered by this licence. | `120` |
| `pasture_region` | String | Yes | Administrative region in which the licensed pasture is located. | `Yorkshire Dales` |
| `holding_number` | String | Yes | County Parish Holding (CPH) number, as registered with the Rural Payments Agency. | `12/345/0006` |
| `licence_type` | String | Yes | Type of licence. One of `standard`, `breeding`, or `movement`. | `breeding` |
| `issuing_authority` | String | Yes | The authority that issued this licence. | `DEFRA` |
| `issuing_country` | String | Yes | ISO 3166-1 alpha-2 country code for the issuing country. | `GB` |

## Update your issuer metadata

Your `/.well-known/openid-credential-issuer` metadata must declare your custom
namespace credential. The structure is the same as for the mDL, with one key
difference: the `claims` object uses your namespace string — including the version
suffix — as its key, not `org.iso.18013.5.1`.

The key inside `credential_configurations_supported` must match the `doctype`
value exactly:

```json
{
  "credential_issuer": "https://sheep-licence.defra.gov.uk",
  "authorization_servers": ["https://token.account.gov.uk"],
  "credential_endpoint": "https://sheep-licence.defra.gov.uk/credential",
  "notification_endpoint": "https://sheep-licence.defra.gov.uk/notification",
  "credential_configurations_supported": {
    "uk.gov.defra.sheep-licence": {
      "format": "mso_mdoc",
      "doctype": "uk.gov.defra.sheep-licence",
      "credential_refresh_web_journey_url": "https://sheep-licence.defra.gov.uk/refresh",
      "credential_validity_period_max_days": 365,
      "cryptographic_binding_methods_supported": ["did:key"],
      "credential_signing_alg_values_supported": ["ES256"],
      "proof_types_supported": {
        "jwt": {
          "proof_signing_alg_values_supported": ["ES256"]
        }
      },
      "claims": {
        "uk.gov.defra.sheep-licence.1": {
          "licence_number":       { "mandatory": true },
          "holder_family_name":   { "mandatory": true },
          "holder_given_name":    { "mandatory": true },
          "holder_date_of_birth": { "mandatory": true },
          "issue_date":           { "mandatory": true },
          "expiry_date":          { "mandatory": true },
          "sheep_count":          { "mandatory": true },
          "pasture_region":       { "mandatory": true },
          "holding_number":       { "mandatory": true },
          "licence_type":         { "mandatory": true },
          "issuing_authority":    { "mandatory": true },
          "issuing_country":      { "mandatory": true }
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

Note that:

- the key inside `claims` (`"uk.gov.defra.sheep-licence.1"`) is the namespace string, not the docType — it includes the `.1` version suffix
- `credential_validity_period_max_days` of 365 reflects a 1-year sheep licence; use the value you agreed with the GOV.UK Wallet onboarding team
- set `"mandatory": false` for any element that may be absent for some holders

See [Publish your metadata](/issue-a-credential/metadata/) for full guidance on the metadata endpoint.

## Build the credential

The process for encoding data elements, computing hashes, building the MSO, and
signing with COSE_Sign1 is identical to the steps in
[Create an mdoc credential](/issue-a-credential/mdoc/). The only change is that
you use your custom namespace string in place of `org.iso.18013.5.1`.

### Use your namespace in IssuerNameSpaces

The namespace string is the key in `IssuerNameSpaces`:

```
IssuerNameSpaces = {
  "uk.gov.defra.sheep-licence.1" => [
    IssuerSignedItemBytes,  ; licence_number
    IssuerSignedItemBytes,  ; holder_family_name
    IssuerSignedItemBytes,  ; holder_given_name
    IssuerSignedItemBytes,  ; holder_date_of_birth
    IssuerSignedItemBytes,  ; issue_date
    IssuerSignedItemBytes,  ; expiry_date
    IssuerSignedItemBytes,  ; sheep_count
    IssuerSignedItemBytes,  ; pasture_region
    IssuerSignedItemBytes,  ; holding_number
    IssuerSignedItemBytes,  ; licence_type
    IssuerSignedItemBytes,  ; issuing_authority
    IssuerSignedItemBytes   ; issuing_country
  ]
}
```

### Use your namespace in the MSO ValueDigests

The same namespace string is the key in `ValueDigests` inside the Mobile Security
Object:

```
ValueDigests = {
  "uk.gov.defra.sheep-licence.1" => {
    0: bstr,   ; SHA-256 digest of tagged IssuerSignedItem for licence_number
    1: bstr,   ; SHA-256 digest for holder_family_name
    2: bstr,   ; SHA-256 digest for holder_given_name
    3: bstr,   ; SHA-256 digest for holder_date_of_birth
    4: bstr,   ; SHA-256 digest for issue_date
    5: bstr,   ; SHA-256 digest for expiry_date
    6: bstr,   ; SHA-256 digest for sheep_count
    7: bstr,   ; SHA-256 digest for pasture_region
    8: bstr,   ; SHA-256 digest for holding_number
    9: bstr,   ; SHA-256 digest for licence_type
    10: bstr,  ; SHA-256 digest for issuing_authority
    11: bstr   ; SHA-256 digest for issuing_country
  }
}
```

<%= warning_text('The namespace string in IssuerNameSpaces and ValueDigests must be identical. A mismatch will cause GOV.UK Wallet to reject the credential during verification.') %>

### Set the docType in MobileDocument

```
MobileDocument = {
  "docType"      : "uk.gov.defra.sheep-licence",
  "issuerSigned" : IssuerSigned,
  "deviceSigned" : DeviceSigned
}
```

The `docType` in `MobileDocument` must match the `docType` in the MSO exactly.

## Use the example credential issuer

The [GOV.UK Wallet example credential issuer](https://github.com/govuk-one-login/mobile-wallet-example-credential-issuer)
is a reference Java implementation you can use as a starting point. It uses
`@Namespace` annotations to declare which namespace each data element belongs to.
To adapt it for a new credential type, you create a class with a field for each
data element, and annotate each field with your namespace string:

```java
@Namespace("uk.gov.defra.sheep-licence.1")
private String licenceNumber;

@Namespace("uk.gov.defra.sheep-licence.1")
private Integer sheepCount;
```

The example issuer handles CBOR encoding, digest computation, and COSE_Sign1
signing automatically once the class and namespace are defined.

Contact the GOV.UK Wallet onboarding team for access to the example issuer and
for help adapting it to your credential type.

